{ @@HeaderStart@@Closed Position, Bad Bishop@@HeaderEnd@@  In positions with pawn chains, the bishop has limited mobility, and therefore is sometimes weaker than the knight. The chief reason for a bishop being bad is that its own pawns are fixed on the same color squares as the bishop.  Zubarev - Alexandrov, Moscow 1915  The exploitation of the knights indisputable advantage over the bishop is uncomplicated, but quite instructive. First and foremost,  the king must be made as active as possible,  and there is an open road for him straight to c5. }
1. Kf2 Ke7
{ On   1...Kf7  White neutralizes his opponent's activity on the kingside by erecting a  barrier :  2.Ke2 !  Kg6  3.Ne3 !  Kg5  4.g3 !  after which the king continues its march to c5. }
2. Ke3 Kd8 3. Kd4 Kc7 4. Kc5 Bc8
{ The next phase flows from the two-weaknesses principle. White cannot yet win on the queenside alone; therefore he sends the knight  (via f4)  to the kingside, to harry the enemy pawns. These in turn will have to be advanced, which will make them much weaker than they are in their initial positions. }
5. Nb4 Bb7 6. g3
{ It's useful to deprive the opponent of tactical chances   (such as ...d5-d4)  . }
6... Bc8 7. Nd3 Bd7 8. Nf4 { ∆ 9 Nh5 } 8... g6 9. Nh3 { ∆ 10 Ng5 } 9... h6 10.
Nf4 g5 11. Nh5 Be8 12. Nf6 Bf7 *

