{ Johannes Steckner, a Swiss player, while checking the analysis of one of the basic positions which had been considered drawn, found a tremendous improvement for White, leading to a win for him. And his discovery led, in turn, to new researches which were conducted by Steckner, grandmasters Karsten Müller and Rustem Dautov, along with other endgame connoisseurs. The results of our research are reflected in the Russian edition of the Endgame Manual, as well as the second and third releases of the American edition and the second, third and fourth releases of the German edition.  The development of this theory has not remained static. In late 2011, an Armenian chess aficionado, Vardan Pogosyan, provided additional support that the position under consideration was nevertheless still drawn. Pogosyan also made substantial refinements in the analysis of other endings included in this section of the Endgame Manual.  Here I shall present only the most important and interesting variations, omitting many of the analytical details. For those who seek more detailed information, I would recommend visiting @@LinkStart@@www.chesscafe.com@@LinkEnd@@ and looking for my article published in October/November 2003, as well as articles by Karsten Müller, the last of which, dedicated to Pogosyans discoveries, was published in March 2012.  Nevertheless, even in edited form, the material I offer for your consideration is so large and complex, that it clearly exceeds the boundaries I tried to maintain when I wrote this Endgame Manual. The excuse I offer is its newness and enormous practical significance to the theory of this sort of endgame.  Nothing could be further from my mind than to label the analysis presented below as the last word of theory, for long, complicated variations rarely turn out error-free. But in any case, they go a long way to correct and develop the pre-existing conclusions, and may in turn serve as a starting point for additional theoretical researches.  V. Kantorovich, 1988, J. Steckner, 2003  In 1989, Vadim Kantorovich, of Moscow, published an interesting article titled, The Outside Passed Pawn. The article opened with the diagrammed position. The main conclusion of the analysis was: Black draws with two tempi to spare. In fact, he is almost lost.  But, it turns out, almost ! }
