{ @@HeaderStart@@Checkmating with Two Knights@@HeaderEnd@@  Driving the king to the edge of the board is an easy task. Alas, you can only stalemate it thereafter, not checkmate, but three knights will win against a single knight.   However  if the defender has a pawn, and this pawn is not too advanced, and it is blocked with one of the knights, an eventual win is quite possible,  although the winning process is very difficult; it may require dozens of precise moves.   As the Russian study composer Troitsky proved in the beginning of the 20th century, a knight together with a king can drive the solitary king either to a corner or towards the spare knight  (the one that is blocking the pawn)  . Thereafter, the spare knight joins the hunt, and mate is delivered with its help. }
