{ @@HeaderStart@@A Fortified Camp@@HeaderEnd@@  We define this as a situation in which a king, with or without the assistance of pieces or pawns, successfully defends a small territory  (as a rule, in a corner)  and cannot be ousted. Almost all the theoretical fortresses that are already known to you belong in this category. I add only a single, more complicated example here.  F. Simkhovich, 1926  The h3-pawn will inevitably be promoted. Whites only chance for a successful defense consists in building a fortress: f5-f6 and Kf8-g7. But to build a reliable fortress he needs to place his bishop on h6. Otherwise Black brings his king to f5, takes the knight with his queen and captures the g5-pawn, winning. The question is whether White can perform this task in time.  The natural   1.f6 ?  loses:  h2  2.Kf8  h1=Q  3.Kg7   3.Kg8  Kd7  4.Bf8  Qa8 !  ∆ ...Ke6-f5 +-  3...Kc6  4.Nf8  Qh4  5.Nh7  Kd5  6.Ba3  Ke4  7.Bb4  Kf5  8.Bd2  Qf2  9.Bc1  Qe1  10.Ba3  Qh1  -+  followed by 11... Qxh7+. }
1. Bf6 Kd6 { 1...h2 ?  2.Be5+ } 2. Be7+ Kc6
{ The king has been forced to occupy a square on the h1-a8 diagonal. This is precisely what White wanted.  Simkhovich included the moves   2...Ke5  3.Bd8  But after 2... Ke5, White has a simpler draw:   3.fxg6  fxg6  4.Kd7 =  3...Kd6  4.Be7+  and only now  Kc6 }
3. f6 h2 4. Bf8
{ Rather than   4.Kf8 ?  h1=Q  5.Kg8  Qh2  6.Bf8  Qb8 !  7.Kg7  Kd7  etc. }
4... h1=Q 5. Bh6
{ The queen cannot deliver a check from a8, and the white king comes to g7 safely. White has successfully built an impregnable fortress. }
